WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.428
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:08.177 --> 00:00:09.760
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
Honored to be joined

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:13.360
by Sebastian Junger who's
made amazing documentaries

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:14.855
such as "Restrepo."

00:00:14.855 --> 00:00:18.430
His newest one is called
"Hell on Earth" about Syria.

00:00:18.430 --> 00:00:22.010
And he's also the author
of the book called "Tribe."

00:00:22.010 --> 00:00:24.950
So let's give Sebastian
a warm Google welcome.

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:26.450
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Thank you.

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:27.055
Thank you.

00:00:27.055 --> 00:00:28.930
JORDAN THIBODEAU: So
we're going to start off

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:32.540
talking about "Hell on Earth."

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:35.515
Maybe we can go
into why you decided

00:00:35.515 --> 00:00:39.490
to jump into that topic, what
inspired you to get involved?

00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:44.290
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: So I became a
war reporter in the early '90s.

00:00:44.290 --> 00:00:46.240
I went to Sarajevo, to Bosnia.

00:00:46.240 --> 00:00:50.920
This is of course before the US
was involved as a peacekeeping

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:52.520
force.

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:55.310
And I continued covering civil
wars throughout the '90s.

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:59.850
I first went to
Afghanistan in 1996.

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:01.600
I watched as the
Taliban prepared

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:06.820
to overrun Kabul and Jalalabad,
and then again in 2000.

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:09.160
Then I was in Sierra
Leone and Liberia.

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:13.780
Most of my experience
as a war reporter

00:01:13.780 --> 00:01:16.600
has been with the local
population and in wars

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:20.560
that the US wasn't involved
in and wasn't thinking about.

00:01:20.560 --> 00:01:23.950
And then my colleague
and I, Tim Hetherington,

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:26.710
spent time with US forces
in Eastern Afghanistan

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:30.130
in Kunar Province and made a
documentary called "Restrepo."

00:01:30.130 --> 00:01:31.600
We went to the Oscars.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.920
We were nominated for an Oscar.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:33.844
We didn't win.

00:01:33.844 --> 00:01:35.260
A few weeks later
we were supposed

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:40.090
to go on assignment to Libya
to cover the Libyan civil war.

00:01:40.090 --> 00:01:42.781
It was part of the sort
of Arab Spring uprisings

00:01:42.781 --> 00:01:45.280
that were so interesting and
complicated, really complicated

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:46.615
moment for the Arab world.

00:01:46.615 --> 00:01:49.120
At the last minute
I couldn't go.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:52.180
Tim went on his own and he got
killed in the city of Misrata.

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:54.490
He was hit by
fragments from a mortar

00:01:54.490 --> 00:01:56.340
fired by Gaddafi's forces.

00:01:56.340 --> 00:01:59.200
And he bled out in the back
of a pickup truck from a wound

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:04.870
that I think didn't
necessarily have to be mortal.

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:07.410
No one around him
knew what to do.

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:10.807
Not the rebels and not
the other journalists

00:02:10.807 --> 00:02:12.140
had any medical training at all.

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:15.010
He just bled out a few
minutes from a hospital.

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:20.110
And after that, I decided
to stop war reporting.

00:02:20.110 --> 00:02:25.550
But Syria turned into sort
of the worst case scenario.

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:27.259
I mean all the Arab
Spring countries went

00:02:27.259 --> 00:02:28.550
through what they went through.

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:29.650
Tunisia ended pretty well.

00:02:29.650 --> 00:02:32.350
Libya is still pretty rocky
but it's quieted down.

00:02:32.350 --> 00:02:37.750
Syria was just full-on
bloodbath, 400,000 people dead

00:02:37.750 --> 00:02:41.650
at this point,
millions of refugees,

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:45.460
a lot of international interests
converging on the problem

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:46.720
and making it worse.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.010
And so my colleague
and I, Nick Quested,

00:02:51.010 --> 00:02:54.220
decided we really had to
examine the case of Syria.

00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:55.060
How did it start?

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:55.910
What went wrong?

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:57.580
Why is there a civil war there?

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:01.360
And particularly, how did
ISIS come out of this?

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:04.810
Syria is the only country that
produced something like ISIS.

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:07.900
ISIS really is just sort of
remarkable in its depravity

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:13.030
and its violence and its
pretension to religious purity.

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:17.200
And so we just felt it was an
important thing to explain.

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:19.570
And of course you
want to make something

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:22.430
that helps people come to a
good decision about what to do.

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:24.757
And that's always in the
back of any journalist's mind

00:03:24.757 --> 00:03:25.590
or filmmaker's mind.

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:27.989
So that's how we wound
up focusing in Syria.

00:03:27.989 --> 00:03:29.030
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Gotcha.

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:31.480
And so you used
Syrians on the ground

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:33.121
to record your
footage and whatnot?

00:03:33.121 --> 00:03:35.620
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah, I mean
for the first time in my life

00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:37.634
I made a film and wasn't
on the ground shooting.

00:03:37.634 --> 00:03:39.550
In fact I didn't even
leave the United States.

00:03:39.550 --> 00:03:40.425
I was writing a book.

00:03:40.425 --> 00:03:44.740
I was writing my book
"Tribe" and promoting it.

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:46.300
Nick went overseas.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:49.021
It was a suicide mission
to go into Syria itself.

00:03:49.021 --> 00:03:51.520
They were kidnapping journalists
and cutting their heads off

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:52.480
on camera.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:56.500
I mean, danger on the
battlefield is one thing.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:03.370
The risk of being kidnapped
and executed is an entirely

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:05.770
different kind of risk that
really almost no one has

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:07.840
the stomach for, and
I certainly don't.

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:10.930
So what we were able to do,
what Nick was able to do

00:04:10.930 --> 00:04:13.450
was along the
Turkish-Syrian border,

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:15.370
he found people,
fixers, and people

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:18.550
who had family in
Syria, friends in Syria,

00:04:18.550 --> 00:04:21.050
he found people that
knew people in Syria who

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:24.100
were documenting their own
civil war with cameras.

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:26.350
And we started working with
and we would get cameras

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:27.430
to people in there.

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:29.320
We started working
with people who

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:33.010
were stuck in the Civil War,
either just the civilians

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:34.690
or they were Syrian
cameramen who

00:04:34.690 --> 00:04:37.144
wanted to document what was
happening to their country.

00:04:37.144 --> 00:04:39.060
We started working with
them sort of remotely.

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:40.796
We would get thumb
drives into them.

00:04:40.796 --> 00:04:41.920
We'd get cameras into them.

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:44.380
We'd give them
shooting instructions.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.300
And then we'd get this
material back out.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:50.800
And it was a very, in
some ways, awkward way

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:53.440
to make a film compared to just
being on the ground shooting.

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:56.230
But it also had enormous
advantages in addition

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:57.790
to the fact it was
just safer for us.

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:01.589
But it had other sort of
creative advantages as well.

00:05:01.589 --> 00:05:03.630
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Can you
talk about the backdrop

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:07.330
to Syria, like the
different political entities

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:09.039
that are involved
right now in civil war?

00:05:09.039 --> 00:05:10.496
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Yeah, I mean it's

00:05:10.496 --> 00:05:11.880
super complicated of course.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:15.240
And Nick really was the
expert about that stuff.

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:17.250
I mean he did 30-some
trips over there

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:20.800
and he really got into the
weeds with Syrian politics.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:22.237
He didn't successfully
completely

00:05:22.237 --> 00:05:23.570
drag me into the weeds with him.

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:25.350
But from what I
understand, of course

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:27.030
you've got the Assad regime.

00:05:27.030 --> 00:05:33.790
It's backed by Iran,
heavily aided by Hezbollah,

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:36.120
and backed by the
Russians, by Putin.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:39.300
So no, you're not going
to topple the regime that

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:40.380
has friends like that.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:43.560
Assad's not going anywhere.

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:50.000
In the beginning of the war, the
Free Syrian Army was largely--

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.180
it was the product of a popular
uprising, an uprising that

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:59.550
was protesting not only
the deep, deep corruption

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:04.200
of the Assad regime but also
the just unspeakable brutality

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:07.000
of the security forces
that kept them in power,

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.720
security forces
that were completely

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:13.410
OK with detaining teenage
boys who had sprayed graffiti

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:14.670
on a wall--

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.680
down with Assad, just
something like that--

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:19.770
completely OK with
detaining 15-year-old boys

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:21.720
and torturing them to death.

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:23.220
That was how the
revolution started,

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:27.750
with parents whose
boys had been detained

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:30.157
and were in a police
station, parents

00:06:30.157 --> 00:06:31.740
massing in front of
the police station

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:33.940
demanding the release
of their children,

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:36.750
and finally storming the
police station to save them,

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:40.156
and then the security forces
opening fire on the parents.

00:06:40.156 --> 00:06:41.530
That's how the
civil war started.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:44.760
And sometimes in this country
what I hear from people is.

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:45.372
it's crazy.

00:06:45.372 --> 00:06:46.080
It's a civil war.

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:48.607
If those people want
to kill each other,

00:06:48.607 --> 00:06:49.690
you can't tell them apart.

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:50.820
Just let them kill each other.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.278
You have to
understand, people have

00:06:52.278 --> 00:06:54.540
to understand how
these things start.

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:59.300
They start with obscenities
like that situation in Daraa.

00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:02.190
It's the town of Daraa.

00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:06.280
So the FSA came out of that.

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:10.680
And of course the
longer a war goes on,

00:07:10.680 --> 00:07:15.360
the more chance you have of
a popular and more or less

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:17.730
democratic movement
metastasizing,

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:20.190
having some parts
of it metastasize

00:07:20.190 --> 00:07:23.790
into radicalization,
into really sort

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:28.550
of like vicious
anti-Western thought.

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:32.490
It becomes just as inhuman
and cruel as the regime

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:33.540
they're protesting.

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:36.180
So one of the arguments, one
of the moral and practical

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:39.230
arguments for intervening
early on in civil wars

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:42.370
is that keeps that kind of
radical cancer from starting.

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:44.370
And once it's started,
it's really hard to stop.

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:46.560
I mean just like with
cancer in the human body,

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:49.149
it's really, really
hard to stop.

00:07:49.149 --> 00:07:50.190
And that's what happened.

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:52.860
The FSA splintered.

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:55.740
Some groups got
really radicalized.

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:58.230
Al-Qaeda came in.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:02.820
And eventually ISIS was
sort of incubated and born

00:08:02.820 --> 00:08:07.680
in the vacuum in Iraq
after the US withdrawal

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:11.070
and migrated into Syria
and really took a foothold,

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:13.250
got a foothold in Syria.

00:08:13.250 --> 00:08:14.750
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
In the documentary

00:08:14.750 --> 00:08:17.780
you follow a particular family.

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:21.094
Can you talk about how you guys
got connected to them and maybe

00:08:21.094 --> 00:08:22.760
an update on what the
family's doing now

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:23.890
if you're still in contact?

00:08:23.890 --> 00:08:29.020
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah, so it's
two family of brothers, Marwan

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:30.970
and Radwan.

00:08:30.970 --> 00:08:33.700
One was a garage mechanic,
another at a little cell phone

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:36.574
shop in Aleppo.

00:08:36.574 --> 00:08:37.990
And they were
pushed out of Aleppo

00:08:37.990 --> 00:08:39.760
by the fighting to a
town called Manbij.

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:41.590
ISIS took over Manbij.

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:43.179
They were living
under ISIS control

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:46.540
with their children, their
wives and their children.

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:50.950
And the Russian Air Force
and Assad's air force

00:08:50.950 --> 00:08:55.970
was bombing Manbij
pretty regularly.

00:08:55.970 --> 00:09:02.170
And so what Nick managed to
do was he knew the brother.

00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:05.440
He knew a third brother
that was actually in Turkey.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:08.140
And he said, "Listen,
would you think

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:10.720
those families would
like to document life

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:12.310
under ISIS for us?

00:09:12.310 --> 00:09:15.040
We'll pay them and
they'd shoot for us."

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:16.700
So they agreed to.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:19.480
And so we got them
a camera, like

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:24.040
a very nondescript, low
profile Samsung 7 cell phone

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:26.500
camera basically, the
kind that everybody

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:28.900
has so they're not calling
attention to themselves.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:30.940
And they self-documented.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:35.137
They documented their lives
under ISIS, the conversations

00:09:35.137 --> 00:09:36.970
they had about if they
should try to escape,

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:39.370
what are the risks of escaping?

00:09:39.370 --> 00:09:42.190
And they documented
the escape itself.

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:43.870
They were basically
under a tarpaulin

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:49.420
in the back of a truck driving
through ISIS checkpoints

00:09:49.420 --> 00:09:52.390
through no man's land into
FSA territory, eventually

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:53.580
into Turkey.

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:55.750
And keep in mind, just
imagine, those of you

00:09:55.750 --> 00:09:58.250
who have children, doing
a journey like that,

00:09:58.250 --> 00:10:00.340
knowing that if you get
stopped at a checkpoint

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:02.905
and they pull the tarpaulin
back and they discover you,

00:10:02.905 --> 00:10:05.560
you and your family will be
lined up and machine gunned.

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:07.060
That's what the stakes were.

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:08.680
And they documented all this.

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:10.270
And thank God they
got out safely.

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:12.280
They got to Turkey.

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:15.540
Nick met them in Turkey
and got to meet them

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:18.430
and then started
shooting them himself.

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.950
And then they continued
on with their camera

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.840
onto a Zodiac, a rubber Zodiac
trying to get to Greece,

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:25.676
and the last moment
were turned back

00:10:25.676 --> 00:10:26.800
by the Turkish Coast Guard.

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:30.820
So some of the most
extraordinary parts of the film

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:35.360
are parts that just
this family shot.

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:39.760
And really, it's a whole new way
of thinking about filmmaking.

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:42.310
Even if we'd been
able to go in there,

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:44.050
it would have been
like a Westerner

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:47.110
with a video camera in
the middle of this very

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:48.370
intimate family situation.

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:49.800
It would have altered it.

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:52.480
It would not be the reality
that you're seeing here.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:56.980
And so really there is something
to be said for asking people

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:00.980
to self-document as long as
you can trust that they're not

00:11:00.980 --> 00:11:02.000
manipulating you.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.579
And that's the only
downside to it.

00:11:04.579 --> 00:11:06.120
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
And there's a scene

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:09.980
when one of the families, the
husband and wife are talking

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.320
and he was making a decision
if they should flee or not.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:15.120
And they were arguing
right in front

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:17.150
of like six of their children.

00:11:17.150 --> 00:11:19.090
And it just really
hit home about

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:20.799
how terrible the crisis is.

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:23.090
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah, I
mean they're stuck in Turkey,

00:11:23.090 --> 00:11:25.430
so they're safe, but
they're miserable.

00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:28.550
And they're arguing about
whether to risk the boat

00:11:28.550 --> 00:11:29.426
passage.

00:11:29.426 --> 00:11:30.800
And you all know,
there are a lot

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:32.510
of people drowned, a
lot of loss of life

00:11:32.510 --> 00:11:35.630
on these Zodiacs
of people trying

00:11:35.630 --> 00:11:41.030
to get from North Africa to
Europe from Turkey to Greece.

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:43.040
And the wife is like--

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:46.010
the mother is saying,
one big wave and I

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:47.950
lose all my children.

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:52.370
And he is saying, OK, but
at least we'll die together.

00:11:52.370 --> 00:11:54.040
And right now we're
stuck in Turkey.

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:56.350
Our children have
no future at all.

00:11:56.350 --> 00:12:01.120
I say it's better that we
gamble on giving them a future

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:04.930
or we die together
and that's God's will.

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:08.230
And the husband eventually
won the argument.

00:12:11.379 --> 00:12:13.420
JORDAN THIBODEAU: There's
an argument in the West

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:18.220
that during all this chaos
that the people who are leading

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:20.500
should stay there and they
should fight or something.

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:22.630
But I think after
watching this documentary

00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:24.940
you realize how much
of a terrible situation

