from watching a lot of films

00:37:45.079 --> 00:37:46.370
and from making a lot of films.

00:37:46.370 --> 00:37:48.650
A hundred minutes seems to
be just about the limit.

00:37:48.650 --> 00:37:50.358
I mean you can go to
two hours, whatever.

00:37:50.358 --> 00:37:52.520
But if you go to
two hours, trust me,

00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:54.830
the audience will know
you've gone to two hours.

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:57.320
And you really don't want
your audience thinking

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:58.910
about how long the film is.

00:37:58.910 --> 00:38:00.535
As soon as that--

00:38:00.535 --> 00:38:01.410
you know what I mean?

00:38:01.410 --> 00:38:03.493
It's like on a first date
you don't want your date

00:38:03.493 --> 00:38:06.320
thinking, wow, we've been
having dinner for two hours.

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:08.450
That's not a good sign.

00:38:08.450 --> 00:38:09.837
Same with filmmaking.

00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:17.240
AUDIENCE: So I wanted to
understand your viewpoint

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:19.740
on ISIS vis-a-vis the Taliban.

00:38:19.740 --> 00:38:23.330
They seemed to have
had similar structures

00:38:23.330 --> 00:38:25.160
in terms of carving
out territory,

00:38:25.160 --> 00:38:29.580
providing basic services,
promises and the rest.

00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:33.200
But ISIS is a bit more
brutal of course it seems.

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:34.724
So what's your take?

00:38:34.724 --> 00:38:36.140
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Oh yeah, I mean,

00:38:36.140 --> 00:38:40.070
the Taliban were conducting
public executions.

00:38:40.070 --> 00:38:46.190
They were stoning adulterers in
the sports arena, for example.

00:38:46.190 --> 00:38:48.560
But the Taliban weren't
a terrorist organization.

00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:51.410
I mean, they were terroristic
towards their own population.

00:38:51.410 --> 00:38:55.290
I think they're
extremely abusive.

00:38:55.290 --> 00:38:58.340
And so are a lot of
right-wing regimes as well.

00:38:58.340 --> 00:39:00.150
Brutality is brutality.

00:39:00.150 --> 00:39:01.820
But they weren't
attacking the West.

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:03.710
And from the West's
perspective--

00:39:03.710 --> 00:39:05.060
and we are Westerners, right?

00:39:05.060 --> 00:39:08.160
From our perspective, you become
a terrorist when you attack us.

00:39:08.160 --> 00:39:11.926
AUDIENCE: Weren't they
housing Osama bin Laden--

00:39:11.926 --> 00:39:13.050
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Well yes.

00:39:13.050 --> 00:39:16.950
AUDIENCE: --and thus--
it seemed like they

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:18.690
were housing Osama bin Laden.

00:39:18.690 --> 00:39:22.405
And so it was this default
attack on the West.

00:39:22.405 --> 00:39:24.030
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Absolutely they were,

00:39:24.030 --> 00:39:25.170
and that was problematic.

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:27.090
But they themselves,
they started

00:39:27.090 --> 00:39:28.990
in the madrassas of Pakistan.

00:39:28.990 --> 00:39:35.190
Their entire focus was bringing
their vision of sort of pure

00:39:35.190 --> 00:39:40.530
and, we would argue, radical
Islam to Afghanistan.

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:42.160
That was the their entire focus.

00:39:42.160 --> 00:39:43.920
They weren't trying
to use Afghanistan

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:45.480
as a base to attack the West.

00:39:45.480 --> 00:39:48.660
Now they did host bin
Laden and al-Qaeda

00:39:48.660 --> 00:39:51.930
is a terrorist organization.

00:39:51.930 --> 00:39:54.360
And they finally really
got our attention.

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:56.790
I mean it took a while to
get our attention, right?

00:39:56.790 --> 00:39:58.860
I mean al-Qaeda
attacked us a few times,

00:39:58.860 --> 00:40:01.000
and we kept sort of like,
oh, OK, that didn't hurt.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:02.130
That didn't hurt too much.

00:40:02.130 --> 00:40:04.860
I mean, it took a few tries
before we actually really

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:06.310
focused on them.

00:40:06.310 --> 00:40:08.970
And of course that was 9/11.

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:11.880
And after 9/11 happened,
the United States was like--

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:17.530
I mean George Bush said
to the Taliban leadership,

00:40:17.530 --> 00:40:19.850
turn over al-Qaeda.

00:40:19.850 --> 00:40:22.007
Turn over the
al-Qaeda leadership,

00:40:22.007 --> 00:40:23.340
we will not invade your country.

00:40:23.340 --> 00:40:25.673
We'll actually come and help
you, because you need help.

00:40:28.380 --> 00:40:31.470
If you don't turn them over,
we will come after them.

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:34.240
And you will become
our enemy as well.

00:40:34.240 --> 00:40:35.490
I didn't vote for George Bush.

00:40:35.490 --> 00:40:37.630
I disagreed with a
lot of his policies,

00:40:37.630 --> 00:40:41.130
but I thought that was an
incredibly sort of sage

00:40:41.130 --> 00:40:44.730
and reasonable reaction.

00:40:44.730 --> 00:40:48.390
In the heat of the moment after
9/11 that he did that I thought

00:40:48.390 --> 00:40:50.340
was really admirable.

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:54.460
Very stupidly the Taliban said,
no, no, no, they're our guests.

00:40:54.460 --> 00:40:56.230
And we went in and got them.

00:40:56.230 --> 00:40:59.280
It took a while and we made
a huge number of mistakes,

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:01.440
but that was a war
that made sense to me.

00:41:01.440 --> 00:41:03.690
I mean I was over there
in 2000 with Massoud

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:04.950
fighting the Taliban.

00:41:04.950 --> 00:41:06.900
I was there in 2001
with his commanders

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:09.840
when they took Kabul, with
the US Air Force overhead.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:12.112
The Afghans were overjoyed
at what was happening.

00:41:12.112 --> 00:41:14.070
We could have done a huge
amount of good there.

00:41:14.070 --> 00:41:15.600
We really could have.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:18.630
We left 15,000 troops
in Afghanistan.

00:41:18.630 --> 00:41:21.150
15,000, that's it.

00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:23.290
There's 40,000 cops
in New York City.

00:41:23.290 --> 00:41:26.970
We left 15,000 American
soldiers in the country

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:30.360
that produced the worst
attack on American soil

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:32.430
since Pearl Harbor.

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:34.350
And we went on to
Iraq, a country

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:36.190
that had nothing to do with it.

00:41:36.190 --> 00:41:39.930
And we lost the war in
Afghanistan in Baghdad

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:42.400
basically, in my opinion.

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:48.310
And so the Taliban and
ISIS, what do they share?

00:41:51.050 --> 00:41:53.900
In terms of their vision of
Islam and how to run a society,

00:41:53.900 --> 00:41:55.160
they're very similar.

00:41:55.160 --> 00:41:58.010
ISIS is more extreme, a
little more spectacular

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:02.660
in their brutality, definitely
more media savvy for sure.

00:42:02.660 --> 00:42:05.660
But it's the same
radical vision of Islam

00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:08.770
that my friend Sarah
Chayes points out.

00:42:08.770 --> 00:42:14.510
And Sarah, she's a childhood
friend, former NPR reporter.

00:42:14.510 --> 00:42:17.150
When 9/11 happened, she went to
Pakistan, bought a motorcycle,

00:42:17.150 --> 00:42:21.440
and drove into Kandahar and
rented a house in Kandahar

00:42:21.440 --> 00:42:24.335
while the Taliban were still
in control of Kandahar.

00:42:24.335 --> 00:42:26.710
She's also a Harvard graduate,
an incredibly smart woman.

00:42:26.710 --> 00:42:28.280
And she really knows
the Arab world.

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:29.930
She learned Pashtun,
really knows

00:42:29.930 --> 00:42:32.600
the Arab world, amazing woman.

00:42:32.600 --> 00:42:34.610
She wrote a book called
"Thieves of State."

00:42:34.610 --> 00:42:36.860
And she examined the
role of corruption.

00:42:36.860 --> 00:42:39.200
And what she found was
that the common denominator

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:41.180
in all these radical
Islamic movements that

00:42:41.180 --> 00:42:43.460
are so brutal and violent--

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:49.390
the Shabaab in Somalia, Boko
Haram, the Taliban, ISIS--

00:42:49.390 --> 00:42:52.330
the common denominator
in all those movements

00:42:52.330 --> 00:42:58.150
is that they got traction
in the population

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:01.840
not because the population loved
the idea of radical Islam--

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:03.490
who would really, right?

00:43:03.490 --> 00:43:07.150
That's not a fun way to live.

00:43:07.150 --> 00:43:08.650
They got traction
because they would

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:13.690
promise to stop the
incredible corruption

00:43:13.690 --> 00:43:15.220
of an oppressive regime.

00:43:15.220 --> 00:43:17.560
Every one of those
countries was just

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:19.750
crippled with
government corruption.

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:22.180
The governments were basically
criminal cartels that

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:24.010
existed to enrich themselves.

00:43:24.010 --> 00:43:27.760
And these radical
movements would say, OK,

00:43:27.760 --> 00:43:31.030
if you adopt our
vision of Islam,

00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:34.450
we will protect you from the
tyranny of this government

00:43:34.450 --> 00:43:35.800
and its corruption.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:38.770
And people reluctantly would be
like, OK, that's a good deal.

00:43:38.770 --> 00:43:42.210
And I remember when I was
in Kabul, Afghanistan,

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:45.970
in the summer of
1996, I got shot

00:43:45.970 --> 00:43:48.040
at by a Taliban
machine gun position

00:43:48.040 --> 00:43:49.910
on the outskirts of town.

00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:53.440
And me and the translator guy
that I-- and he was Afghan.

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:55.180
He was Pashtun-- that
I was working with,

00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:56.060
we got behind cover.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:43:58.100
We got out of there.

00:43:58.100 --> 00:44:01.960
And he said, "We
hate those people.

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:03.070
We hate them.

00:44:03.070 --> 00:44:04.870
But we're going to
let them in because we

00:44:04.870 --> 00:44:07.120
can no longer live with the
corruption of this government.

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:08.870
And they promised to
clean up corruption."

00:44:08.870 --> 00:44:12.040
So if we want to
fight terrorism,

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:14.260
we can fight terrorism
really effectively

00:44:14.260 --> 00:44:17.290
by fighting corruption,
particularly corruption

00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:19.150
with governments that
we're allied with

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:22.510
and do business with,
particularly those governments.

00:44:22.510 --> 00:44:26.540
We won't have to fight terrorism
because it won't gain root.

00:44:26.540 --> 00:44:29.540
We're completely
screwing ourselves

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:34.966
and wasting a lot of lives, lot
of lives of very good people.

00:44:34.966 --> 00:44:36.340
JORDAN THIBODEAU:
That reminds me

00:44:36.340 --> 00:44:38.814
of what happen in Iran
with the fall of the shah.

00:44:38.814 --> 00:44:40.480
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Yeah, of course, yeah.

00:44:40.480 --> 00:44:43.650
AUDIENCE: We have
one more question.

00:44:43.650 --> 00:44:45.270
AUDIENCE: Follow
up question-- do

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:49.320
you see ISIS changing once
they don't hold territory?

00:44:49.320 --> 00:44:51.900
I guess I understand it,
the original ideology

00:44:51.900 --> 00:44:53.660
is they are the caliphate.

00:44:53.660 --> 00:44:55.830
They're following the Quran.

00:44:55.830 --> 00:44:58.810
If they don't hold territory,
they no longer have a mandate.

00:44:58.810 --> 00:45:02.285
Is that completely made up or
do you see anything changing?

00:45:02.285 --> 00:45:03.660
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
I mean, I don't

00:45:03.660 --> 00:45:08.310
know a regime that doesn't
change the rules of the game

00:45:08.310 --> 00:45:11.400
when they lose the game, right?

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:15.524
Including our own
administration.

00:45:15.524 --> 00:45:17.190
You lose a vote in
Congress and you just

00:45:17.190 --> 00:45:21.022
change what the vote
was about, no problem.

00:45:21.022 --> 00:45:22.980
I mean not to pick on
you know who, but I mean,

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:24.390
that's totally human
behavior, right?

00:45:24.390 --> 00:45:25.723
So ISIS is going to do that too.

00:45:25.723 --> 00:45:26.590
I'd do it.

00:45:26.590 --> 00:45:27.910
I mean of course, right?

00:45:27.910 --> 00:45:29.730
So yeah, they lose
their mandate,

00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:31.770
they'll change the
basis for their mandate

00:45:31.770 --> 00:45:33.390
and they'll continue
saying what they

00:45:33.390 --> 00:45:38.800
want to say to expand their
power base, of course.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:41.710
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
kind of this rise of corruption

00:45:41.710 --> 00:45:45.220
and people wanting to combat it.

00:45:45.220 --> 00:45:47.590
But then you also talked
about this tipping point

00:45:47.590 --> 00:45:51.430
where there's this point
where it takes not too

00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:53.140
much to nudge
people into violence

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:55.690
and then the cascade
to civil war.

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:59.440
How, as you've observed
these, would you define as far

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:02.470
as indicators or warnings
that that tipping

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:03.930
point is beginning to happen?

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:05.680
Because I think anytime
you see corruption

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:07.686
there's people that are
fighting against it.

00:46:07.686 --> 00:46:09.310
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I
mean listen, people

00:46:09.310 --> 00:46:11.560
might be willing to die but
they're not willing to let

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:12.400
their children die.

00:46:12.400 --> 00:46:14.350
And when a population
gets to the point

00:46:14.350 --> 00:46:16.870
where there's a reasonable
chance their children will die,

00:46:16.870 --> 00:46:18.430
they will do anything.

00:46:18.430 --> 00:46:21.400
They will walk across
several international borders

00:46:21.400 --> 00:46:23.050
to safety.

00:46:23.050 --> 00:46:25.570
They will sell a kidney
on the black market.

00:46:25.570 --> 00:46:28.090
They will do absolutely
anything, including

00:46:28.090 --> 00:46:31.480
breaking into a
military storehouse

00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:34.790
and grabbing a bunch of AKs
and a couple of magazines

00:46:34.790 --> 00:46:36.040
and fighting as best they can.

00:46:36.040 --> 00:46:37.120
They'll do that.

00:46:37.120 --> 00:46:38.680
So where is that tipping point?

00:46:38.680 --> 00:46:41.890
The tipping point is
when the security forces

00:46:41.890 --> 00:46:44.710
are detaining and torturing and
killing people, particularly

00:46:44.710 --> 00:46:48.940
children, when they're
firing heavy machine gun

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:52.510
fire into crowds of protesting
people who are peaceful--

00:46:52.510 --> 00:46:55.390
mothers, children, whatever.

00:46:55.390 --> 00:46:59.010
When that starts to happen and
if it goes on for too long,

00:46:59.010 --> 00:47:00.177
that's the tipping point.

00:47:00.177 --> 00:47:02.260
And it would be the tipping
point in this country.

00:47:02.260 --> 00:47:04.240
I mean if that happened
in this country,

00:47:04.240 --> 00:47:06.220
we'd all be grabbing
weapons, right?

00:47:06.220 --> 00:47:09.126
I mean to defend our
families, of course.

00:47:09.126 --> 00:47:10.750
I mean, we're the
product of evolution.

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:13.060
We're the products of
individuals that made

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:14.410
certain choices to survive.

00:47:14.410 --> 00:47:15.670
We're the product of that.

00:47:15.670 --> 00:47:17.874
So of course we would
protect ourselves.

00:47:17.874 --> 00:47:19.540
JORDAN THIBODEAU: We
came close to that,

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:21.630
I think, after the
Revolutionary War

00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:23.934
during the Whiskey Rebellion
and the debtors crisis,

00:47:23.934 --> 00:47:25.350
the Continental
soldiers going out

00:47:25.350 --> 00:47:27.210
fighting for the
country and the debtors

00:47:27.210 --> 00:47:29.230
coming and taking
their livelihoods,

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:32.340
and then during the Depression,
during the Bonus Army

00:47:32.340 --> 00:47:35.500
fight when the military
came after the veterans who

00:47:35.500 --> 00:47:38.060
were trying to get their
benefits from World War I.

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:40.154
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah
right, absolutely.

00:47:40.154 --> 00:47:41.820
Human behavior doesn't
change very much.

00:47:45.410 --> 00:47:47.030
AUDIENCE: Hi, how are you doing?

00:47:47.030 --> 00:47:48.609
So I have a question.

00:47:48.609 --> 00:47:50.900
What are your current thoughts
about the situation that

00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:55.040
is happening in Iraq right now
with, they retook the city.

00:47:55.040 --> 00:47:59.840
And there's just this huge power
vacuum between the Iraqi Kurds

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:02.199
and with the other people
involved in the government.

00:48:02.199 --> 00:48:03.490
What are your thoughts on that?

00:48:03.490 --> 00:48:07.160
What's the future for Iraq
looking like right now?

00:48:07.160 --> 00:48:08.930
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I
mean, I don't know.

00:48:08.930 --> 00:48:10.370
I'm not an expert and I never--

00:48:10.370 --> 00:48:12.770
I didn't cover Iraq
because I didn't

00:48:12.770 --> 00:48:13.910
think I could be objective.

00:48:13.910 --> 00:48:16.676
I mean back in '03 I
was so against the war.

00:48:16.676 --> 00:48:18.800
And I wasn't at all against
the war in Afghanistan.

00:48:18.800 --> 00:48:20.316
I thought we could do some good.

00:48:20.316 --> 00:48:21.690
I was so against
the war in Iraq,

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:23.465
I refused to cover
it because I didn't

00:48:23.465 --> 00:48:24.590
think I could be objective.

00:48:24.590 --> 00:48:26.290
So I'm not an expert in Iraq.

00:48:26.290 --> 00:48:26.840
I'm guessing.

00:48:31.100 --> 00:48:34.760
Things tend to slide towards
violence in countries that

00:48:34.760 --> 00:48:35.890
are destabilized like that.

00:48:35.890 --> 00:48:37.848
And those are obviously
destabilized countries.

00:48:37.848 --> 00:48:40.600
And they're also, at this
point, deeply traumatized.

00:48:40.600 --> 00:48:43.100
Everyone in those countries has
been exposed to really quite

00:48:43.100 --> 00:48:44.060
a lot of violence.

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:47.060
And so I'm guessing.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:51.860
I'm just going to guess
that that vacuum will

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:56.750
create turf wars
that will trigger

00:48:56.750 --> 00:48:59.390
another phase of a regional war.

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:01.990
I hope not, but I
wouldn't be surprised.

00:49:01.990 --> 00:49:04.490
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Think about
the psychology of the children

00:49:04.490 --> 00:49:06.800
since we've been in
Afghanistan since 2001.

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:09.170
Now there's kids who have
been alive for 16 years

00:49:09.170 --> 00:49:10.475
and all they've known is war.

00:49:10.475 --> 00:49:13.030
Or then with Iraq, all they've
known is war for 14 years.

00:49:13.030 --> 00:49:15.040
I mean that must have a--

00:49:15.040 --> 00:49:19.300
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah, I
mean, we're almost at the point

00:49:19.300 --> 00:49:23.980
where young American soldiers
fighting in Afghanistan

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:27.994
were born after 9/11, that
were not alive on 9/11.

00:49:27.994 --> 00:49:28.910
That's pretty amazing.

00:49:31.666 --> 00:49:33.040
As far as the
Afghans go, there's

00:49:33.040 --> 00:49:37.590
children whose parents
have known nothing but war.

00:49:37.590 --> 00:49:40.680
I mean, it's incredible.

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:43.080
And it's not their
fault. They didn't ask

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:45.240
to be invaded by the Soviets.

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:47.730
They didn't ask to have
America load their country full

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:49.380
of weapons and then pull out.

00:49:49.380 --> 00:49:51.240
They didn't ask for any of that.

00:49:51.240 --> 00:49:53.730
They didn't ask to
have Pakistan arm

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:57.630
and organize and train a
radical Islamic militia

00:49:57.630 --> 00:50:00.210
and send it across the borders
as the Taliban to take over.

00:50:00.210 --> 00:50:01.543
They didn't ask for any of that.

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:06.160
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
being here Sebastian.

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:07.710
It's been very
interesting to hear

00:50:07.710 --> 00:50:09.346
you speak about this so far.

00:50:09.346 --> 00:50:11.220
I just have a question
about the documentary.

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:15.030
And you mentioned the method
was self-documentation.

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:17.460
So I'm assuming
that you and Nick,

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:20.010
seeing the footage
after the fact

00:50:20.010 --> 00:50:21.985
and on the cutting
room floor and kind

00:50:21.985 --> 00:50:24.360
of going through all of this,
what was that process like?

00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:26.610
I imagine it must have
been intense at points

00:50:26.610 --> 00:50:33.444
to see certain parts that were
recorded days or weeks after.

00:50:33.444 --> 00:50:34.860
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Yeah, of course.

00:50:34.860 --> 00:50:37.110
Yeah, some of the
footage was upsetting.

00:50:37.110 --> 00:50:40.680
But mostly your
job as director is

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:44.070
to create a narrative that's
compelling and provides

00:50:44.070 --> 00:50:48.241
a vehicle to communicate
important information.

00:50:48.241 --> 00:50:49.740
I don't want it to
just be a history

00:50:49.740 --> 00:50:52.700
lesson because people won't
watch the full hundred minutes.

00:50:52.700 --> 00:50:55.440
If it's just a series
of personal stories,

00:50:55.440 --> 00:50:58.800
you may allow for a human
connection with the viewers,

00:50:58.800 --> 00:51:01.594
and that's lovely,
and it's important.

00:51:01.594 --> 00:51:03.385
But you also need a
bit of a history lesson

00:51:03.385 --> 00:51:06.700
to understand why those humans
are having that experience.

00:51:06.700 --> 00:51:10.300
So all the different kinds of
footage we had, from the family

00:51:10.300 --> 00:51:12.490
and from the other shooters
we had in the field--

00:51:12.490 --> 00:51:15.940
we had access to a kind
of trove of ISIS footage

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:19.014
that ISIS had shot through
some kind of digital backdoor

00:51:19.014 --> 00:51:21.430
that I don't understand that
someone sort of found for us.

00:51:21.430 --> 00:51:25.900
And so we had access to a sort
of ISIS database of footage

00:51:25.900 --> 00:51:27.400
that they shot.

00:51:27.400 --> 00:51:28.680
So we had all kinds of stuff.

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:30.480
Some of it's super upsetting.

00:51:30.480 --> 00:51:40.670
Some of it was incredibly
motivating and encouraging.

00:51:40.670 --> 00:51:41.840
One of the strange things--

00:51:41.840 --> 00:51:45.170
my book "Tribe" is about this--

00:51:45.170 --> 00:51:47.990
the closer to a front line
you are, the more of a crisis

00:51:47.990 --> 00:51:49.870
there is, the better people act.

00:51:49.870 --> 00:51:52.529
People within their communities
act incredibly well.

00:51:52.529 --> 00:51:55.070
And they act better and better
as things get worse and worse.

00:51:55.070 --> 00:51:56.630
And so one of the things
you see in a war zone

00:51:56.630 --> 00:51:58.640
is people acting with
unbelievable nobility

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:01.550
and generosity and courage,
I mean just extraordinary,

00:52:01.550 --> 00:52:03.800
in a way that they don't
have to in an affluent suburb

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:05.133
like the kind that I grew up in.

00:52:05.133 --> 00:52:06.509
I never saw noble
human behavior.

00:52:06.509 --> 00:52:08.300
I didn't see any bad
human behavior either,

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:10.880
but I certainly didn't see
any courage or anything.

00:52:10.880 --> 00:52:12.874
There wasn't any need
for courage, which

00:52:12.874 --> 00:52:14.040
is actually kind of a shame.

00:52:16.054 --> 00:52:17.970
JORDAN THIBODEAU: We'll
do two more questions.

00:52:17.970 --> 00:52:19.178
I just want to do a question.

00:52:19.178 --> 00:52:21.095
Can you talk about the
White Helmets In Syria?

00:52:21.095 --> 00:52:22.927
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah,
so the White Helmets

00:52:22.927 --> 00:52:24.580
were a civil
defense organization

00:52:24.580 --> 00:52:26.410
that was organized
sort of organically,

00:52:26.410 --> 00:52:32.260
spontaneously to rush into areas
that had been bombed by Assad's

00:52:32.260 --> 00:52:34.510
air force, or later
the Russian Air Force,

00:52:34.510 --> 00:52:36.080
and dig survivors
out of the rubble

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:39.899
and dig the corpses out of the
rubble to give to the families.

00:52:39.899 --> 00:52:41.440
And often those guys
would get killed

00:52:41.440 --> 00:52:44.050
because there'd be a second
bombing attack on the same spot

00:52:44.050 --> 00:52:45.730
to kill the first responders--

00:52:45.730 --> 00:52:49.734
incredibly brave, unbelievably
brave young people doing that.

00:52:53.900 --> 00:52:57.140
AUDIENCE: OK, quick
question, I hope.

00:52:57.140 --> 00:52:59.570
The first is, is
the war on terror

00:52:59.570 --> 00:53:03.680
moving to Africa, as
maybe evident by some

00:53:03.680 --> 00:53:05.420
of the recent accounts?

00:53:05.420 --> 00:53:10.550
And then secondly, you
mentioned Iraq being a mistake.

00:53:10.550 --> 00:53:14.000
Are we on a course
for the same type

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.010
of mistake with North Korea?

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:21.110
And perhaps would your team and
company do the same in terms

00:53:21.110 --> 00:53:24.440
of gathering information
inside North Korea

00:53:24.440 --> 00:53:26.170
like you did with Syria?

00:53:26.170 --> 00:53:28.684
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: That
was a short question?

00:53:28.684 --> 00:53:30.699
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:30.699 --> 00:53:32.990
JORDAN THIBODEAU: We'll give
you 30 minutes to respond.

00:53:32.990 --> 00:53:33.410
Go for it.

00:53:33.410 --> 00:53:35.000
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I don't know
anything about North Korea

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:36.470
other than what I read
in the paper, which

00:53:36.470 --> 00:53:38.220
is the same as what
you read in the paper.

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:39.770
I've got similar
worries I'm sure,

00:53:39.770 --> 00:53:44.510
and also maybe an unrealistic
sense that people don't

00:53:44.510 --> 00:53:48.400
do, just for the hell of it,
the worst thing imaginable,

00:53:48.400 --> 00:53:52.390
like I just have to assume that.

00:53:52.390 --> 00:53:54.370
So is the war on terror
moving to North Africa?

00:53:54.370 --> 00:53:56.830
I mean, it's been there
for 20 years, right?

00:53:56.830 --> 00:53:57.670
I mean the Shabaab--

00:53:57.670 --> 00:54:03.710
I mean in 1993, "Blackhawk
Down," Somalia was already--

00:54:03.710 --> 00:54:05.100
is that terrorism?

00:54:05.100 --> 00:54:07.810
It's an incredibly
troubled place.

00:54:07.810 --> 00:54:10.510
The Shabaab is absolutely
a terror organization,

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:12.760
as is Boko Haram.

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:21.140
And Al-Qaeda-affiliated groups
have existed in the Sahara,

00:54:21.140 --> 00:54:25.220
in this Sahel for
years and years.

00:54:25.220 --> 00:54:26.630
This isn't new.

00:54:26.630 --> 00:54:31.790
And of course we don't want
to fight those wars ourselves.

00:54:31.790 --> 00:54:33.320
We can't fight everywhere.

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:36.250
But those groups are
legitimate threats.

00:54:36.250 --> 00:54:39.830
An al-Qaeda-affiliated group
took over northern Mali

00:54:39.830 --> 00:54:43.670
and overran Timbuktu
and destroyed

00:54:43.670 --> 00:54:48.890
all these beautiful monuments,
Islamic mosques and things,

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:53.090
like destroyed them, and
killed a lot of the population

00:54:53.090 --> 00:54:56.510
and were driven out by French
military action, thank God.

00:54:56.510 --> 00:54:58.530
But I mean, that's
an important issue

00:54:58.530 --> 00:55:00.290
not just for the
security of the West

00:55:00.290 --> 00:55:02.870
but for the dignity and
the safety of the people

00:55:02.870 --> 00:55:05.490
who live in those areas.

00:55:05.490 --> 00:55:09.284
And so we can't
fight all those wars.

00:55:09.284 --> 00:55:10.700
We shouldn't fight
all those wars.

00:55:10.700 --> 00:55:13.400
But one thing we can do is have
military trainers and advisors

00:55:13.400 --> 00:55:16.730
there to help these
military forces

00:55:16.730 --> 00:55:20.755
in those countries that are
often very ill equipped and ill

00:55:20.755 --> 00:55:21.260
trained.

00:55:21.260 --> 00:55:22.790
You just sort of get
them up to speed so they

00:55:22.790 --> 00:55:24.230
can fight their own fights.

00:55:24.230 --> 00:55:28.400
That, to me, is a
completely legitimate use

00:55:28.400 --> 00:55:34.610
of American power and knowledge.

00:55:34.610 --> 00:55:37.250
So no, this isn't new.

00:55:37.250 --> 00:55:42.500
And someone asked me about
US forces in those areas

00:55:42.500 --> 00:55:44.622
and why are we there, and
someone else said, "Oh,

00:55:44.622 --> 00:55:45.455
it's oil interests."

00:55:45.455 --> 00:55:47.270
I'm like, come on.

00:55:47.270 --> 00:55:49.170
I mean first of all,
you drive a damn car,

00:55:49.170 --> 00:55:52.681
so you're not allowed to be
upset about us protecting

00:55:52.681 --> 00:55:54.680
oil interests around the
world as long as you're

00:55:54.680 --> 00:55:56.210
using that shit, right?

00:55:56.210 --> 00:55:59.420
Sorry, that's just
too hypocritical.

00:55:59.420 --> 00:56:02.300
But also, that's
ignoring the fact

00:56:02.300 --> 00:56:04.460
that these
al-Qaeda-affiliated groups

00:56:04.460 --> 00:56:07.520
are incredibly abusive
to the local population.

00:56:07.520 --> 00:56:08.550
Just remember that.

00:56:08.550 --> 00:56:09.466
They're horrible.

00:56:13.130 --> 00:56:15.650
AUDIENCE: So going
back to "Restrepo"

00:56:15.650 --> 00:56:18.620
and "Tribe," have
you given any thought

00:56:18.620 --> 00:56:22.400
to revisiting the platoon
5, 10, 15 years from now

00:56:22.400 --> 00:56:24.590
in the context of "Tribe"?

00:56:24.590 --> 00:56:28.180
And possibly a second
question, expanding "Tribe"

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:32.740
into a feature documentary
is super interesting stuff.

00:56:32.740 --> 00:56:34.850
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
Yeah, thank you.

00:56:34.850 --> 00:56:37.250
The platoon is not a
platoon anymore, obviously.

00:56:37.250 --> 00:56:38.030
It's dispersed.

00:56:38.030 --> 00:56:41.450
And most of those guys are
now out of their military

00:56:41.450 --> 00:56:44.840
and they're leading their lives.

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:46.960
I don't think I'll
track them down.

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:49.730
I don't know quite how I would--

00:56:49.730 --> 00:56:51.679
I don't quite see
the narrative for how

00:56:51.679 --> 00:56:52.970
I would make a film about that.

00:56:52.970 --> 00:56:55.440
AUDIENCE: Because you
talk a lot about PTSD

00:56:55.440 --> 00:56:58.898
and the brotherhood that
comes out of tragic events.

00:57:02.546 --> 00:57:05.800
The guys from my platoon
when I was in Iraq,

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:11.980
I feel like the deepest
brotherhood with them

00:57:11.980 --> 00:57:14.540
just because we went through
the stuff we went through.

00:57:14.540 --> 00:57:17.320
But like my high
school football team,

00:57:17.320 --> 00:57:20.080
before I went to Iraq they
were like my brothers, but then

00:57:20.080 --> 00:57:25.380
now I won't even go to
a high school reunion--

00:57:25.380 --> 00:57:26.575
so in that kind of context.

00:57:29.249 --> 00:57:31.540
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I'm not in
touch with all those guys.

00:57:31.540 --> 00:57:34.060
I'm close to one guy in
particular that we're

00:57:34.060 --> 00:57:36.200
really good friends.

00:57:36.200 --> 00:57:38.855
I'm in some kind of contact
with some of the others.

00:57:38.855 --> 00:57:41.230
I'm not sure they're in that
much contact with each other

00:57:41.230 --> 00:57:42.040
either.

00:57:42.040 --> 00:57:45.610
I'm not sure there's
a real story there.

00:57:45.610 --> 00:57:46.730
I hear what you're saying.

00:57:46.730 --> 00:57:50.200
But I think most
of those guys have

00:57:50.200 --> 00:57:52.780
constructed their own
lives and sort of moved on.

00:57:52.780 --> 00:57:55.589
A few stayed in the
military, but not many.

00:57:55.589 --> 00:57:57.880
If I thought there was story
there, I'd think about it.

00:57:57.880 --> 00:58:03.850
But also, I am moving on
from the topic of war,

00:58:03.850 --> 00:58:06.400
very deliberately.

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:09.040
"Tribe," obviously a little
part of it is about PTSD,

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:12.916
but mostly it's about our
society and community.

00:58:12.916 --> 00:58:16.600
And I'm definitely going to
keep going in that direction.

00:58:16.600 --> 00:58:18.490
I can't imagine having
not covered war.

00:58:18.490 --> 00:58:20.560
It's part of who I am.

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:24.490
I like to think I've
contributed in a good way

00:58:24.490 --> 00:58:26.539
to our country's
conversation about war,

00:58:26.539 --> 00:58:27.580
our understanding of war.

00:58:27.580 --> 00:58:30.580
I mean, I'd like to think
I've done some good.

00:58:30.580 --> 00:58:33.550
The experience has been
sometimes painful but also

00:58:33.550 --> 00:58:37.090
extremely positive for me,
having been a war reporter.

00:58:37.090 --> 00:58:40.240
But I actually want
to move out of that.

00:58:40.240 --> 00:58:46.230
There is a kind of psychological
consequence to engaging

00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:49.380
in war, in the topic of war.

00:58:49.380 --> 00:58:52.687
It doesn't cost nothing,
psychologically and morally.

00:58:52.687 --> 00:58:53.895
And I'm sort of done with it.

00:58:57.607 --> 00:58:59.440
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Well
thank you for joining

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:03.032
us to talk about the "Hell
on Earth" documentary.

00:59:03.032 --> 00:59:04.990
This concludes our first
part of the interview.

00:59:04.990 --> 00:59:07.240
But let's give Sebastian a
round of applause for his time.

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:07.350
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Thank you.

00:59:07.350 --> 00:59:08.550
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:08.550 --> 00:59:10.400
Thank you.

